117. Ausa Palatino] The imperial pa- lace was on the Mons Palatinus, as stated above (S. iv. 31, n.). ‘ Teges ' is any kind of coarse bed-covering (v. 8. vii. 221, ‘ hi- bernae tegetis 3' ix. 140). Augusta was the title of the emperors’ wives, as they all had that of Augustus themselves. ‘ Cucullus ’ was a hood attached to the ‘ lacerna,' which might be thrown over the head for conceal- ment or protection against the weather. Horace describes a man going out on the same errand as Messalina “odoratum caput obscurante lacerna.” (S. ii. 7. 55). See above, i. 62 ; iii. 170.
